<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the Royal Meteorological Society (IPC0029)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Royal Meteorological Society (IPC0029)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Description of submission</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">1. This submission is made on behalf of the Royal Meteorological Society (RMetS). </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#454542; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">The Royal Meteorological Society is the Learned and Professional Society for weather and climate. The Society is a registered charity. Its affairs are run by a Council of Trustees. Council comprises a total of nineteen Officers and Ordinary Members of Council elected at the Annual General Meeting.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#454542; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.3pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">2. The submission was drafted by the Chair of the </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">RMetS’s</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> Climate Science Communications Group (CSCG), incorporating comments from the CSCG members and members of Council. It has been approved by RMetS Council.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> A list of members of the CSCG and of Council are provided in</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> Note 1 </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">below. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">3. The inquiry invites comments with regard to the IPCC’s fifth assessment report (AR5). Our responses refer specifically to the report of Working Group 1 (WG1).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Declaration of interest</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. Members of the CSCG and of Council who were authors of the IPCC 5</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> assessment report did not take part in drafting or approving this submission. For these purposes “authors of the IPCC 5</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> assessment report” was taken to mean Lead Authors, Contributing Lead Authors and Review Editors.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. Declaration of interests of members of the CSCG. Those marked (*) were excluded from taking part in drafting or approving this submission:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">John Mitchell </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">(Reviewer of IPCC 5</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> assessment report; Lead Author in the first three </span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">assessments and Review Editor in the 4</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">assessment report</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">involved in the policy makers summary in the first and third </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">assessment </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">reports and the synthesis report in the third assessment</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Ed Hawkins (Contributing author to the IPCC 5</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> Assessment report)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Tim Palmer* (Review Editor to the IPCC 5</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> Assessment report)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Rowan Sutton* (Contributing Lead Author of IPCC 5</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> assessment report)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. Declaration of interests of members of Council</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Those marked (*) were excluded from taking part in drafti</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">ng or approving this submission</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Joanna Haigh (Contributing author to IPCC 5</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> assessment report</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> and Lead Author on </span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">the third assessment</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">David Stevenson (Contributing author to IPCC 5</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> assessment report)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Liz Howell* (</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">required under BBC Editorial Guidelines to maintain impartiality and </span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">independence within the BBC</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How robust are the conclusions in the AR5 Physical Science Basis report?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The conclusions </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">of the report </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">are graded in terms of probability and confidence. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">We believe this provides a clear description of the robustness of the conclusions. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The most robust conclusions are indicated by high levels </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">f likelihood and/or confidence. Conversely the </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">least robust </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">are assigned low likelihood/confidence.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How much scope is there to question </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">t</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">he report’s conclusions? </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The report draws on the published peer-reviewed literature and as such represents the current scientific understanding, with the conclusions being carefully graded in terms of likelihood/confidence, noting where appropriate the levels of uncertainty.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent does AR5 reflect the range of views among climate scientists?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Given AR5 is a comprehensive synthesi</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">s of the published literature, our judgement is that</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">the report</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> accurately reflects the views of the vast majority of professional climate scientists who are actively working the field.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Can any of the areas of the science now be considered settled as a result of AR5’s publication, if so which?</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">10</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">This depends on how one defines “settled”</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> In its purest interpretation, no area of science is ever settled since the scientific method </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">always </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">allows for new evidence to overturn previously established theories. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">To</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">provide readers with an accurate assessment of the state of scientific understanding</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">the report </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">qualifies many of its conclusions with </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">levels of certainty </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">in the form of likelihood/confidence. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The report </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">makes some unqualified statements when justified, for example, the Summary for Policymakers states that “Each of the last three decades has been successively warmer at the surface than any preceding decade since the 1850s” and “Warming of the climate system is unequivocal”.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What areas need further effort to reduce the levels of uncertainty?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">11</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Scientific research is an on</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">-going process that </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">attempt</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> to reduce </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">the levels of uncertainty in all</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">relevant </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">area</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">s. I</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">t is important to note that in some instances it is reasonable to anticipate that further research may reduce the range of uncertainty, whereas in others the uncerta</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">inty is a fundamental property (</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">for example there will always be a </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">50%</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> chance of </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">tossing a “head” on an unbiased coin</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">There are on-going efforts to narrow the range of uncertainty</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">, for example,</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> in a measure of the climate response with feedbacks to a change in atmospher</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">ic carbon dioxide concentration</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> known as the “climate sensitivity”. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">A key area of climate research where it is anticipated that further progress will reduce uncertainties is in the prediction of the regional detail of climate change</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effective is AR5 and the summary</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> for policymakers in conveying</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">what is meant by </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">uncertainty in scientific terms</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">? Would a focus on risk rather than uncertainty be useful?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">12</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">In general it is </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">challe</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">nging to communicate the </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">scientific </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">meaning of </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">the words </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">“uncertainty” </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">and “risk” because they differ</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">in subtle ways </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">from the</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">common-us</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> of the word</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">s, and indeed the words are used in subtly different ways in other fields such as </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">economics. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Given this, it is always worth testing and evaluating whether statements have been interpreted as intended and exploring alternative ways of communicating. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">full </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">AR5 </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">report including</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">the summary for policymakers us</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> a standardised framew</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">ork for describing </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">uncertaint</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">based around likelihood/confidence quan</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">tifiers</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> as described in the published guidance note on the consistent treatment of uncertainties.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">We note that a</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">n assessment of “risk” would typically incorporate information that is beyond the scope of WG1, but within the scope of WG2 and WG3.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Does the AR5 address the reliability of climate models?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">13</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The R</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">eport devotes </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Chapter 9 to </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">a comprehensive</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">, balanced and realistic</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">evaluation of climate models</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> which is based on the published literature and draws extensively on the results of the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Coupled Model </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Intercomparison</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> Project Phase 5 (CMIP5).</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> As stated in the report</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> (Chapter 9, final draft)</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> c</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">limate models are based on physical principles, and they reproduce many important aspects of observed climate. We agree with the report when it states that both these aspects contribute to </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">confidence in the models’ suitability for their application in detection and attribution studies and for quantitative future predictions and projections</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">”, and when it notes that “w</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">hereas weather and seasonal climate predictions can be regularly verified, climate projections spanning a century or more cannot. This is particularly the case as anthropogenic forcing is driving the climate system toward conditions not previously observed in the instrumental record, and it will always be a limitation.”</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Has AR5 sufficiently explained the reasons behind the widely reported hiatus in the global surface temperature record?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">he report summarised the scientific understanding of recent </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">global </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">average </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">surface </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">temperature change as described in the published literature</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> up to the WG1 publication acceptance cut-off date of 15 March 2013</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. This outlined the factors </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">thought </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">most likely to have contributed to recent changes. This</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> is an </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">on-going and </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">active area of research </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">(see for example </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Coverage bias in the HadCRUT4 temperature series and its impact on recent temperature trends” by </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Cowtan</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> and Way in the Quarterly Journal of the Royal Meteorological Society</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">cepted manuscript online: 12 Nov</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> 2013)</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do the AR5 Physical Science Basis report’s conclusions strengthen or weaken the economic case for action to prevent dangerous climate change? </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">scientific conclusions of the WG1 report </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">provide an evidence base for input into economic </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">discussions</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">n the majority of instances, the </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">scientific </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">conclusions of the AR5 WG1 report are strengthened compared with </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">previous reports</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> in the sense that the conclusions have remained broadly similar but are now supported by more evidence.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> The WG1 report does not comment on the economic case for action to prevent dangerous climate change and this is outside the regime of expertise of the Royal Meteorological Society.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is the IPCC process an effective mechanism for assessing scient</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ific knowledge? Or has it focus</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ed on providing a justification for political commitment?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">We believe that th</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">e IPCC process provides a comprehensive, objective, open and transparent</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> assessment of the state of scientific knowledge.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">We note that </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">process involves</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">a significant commitment from the scientific community with</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> the voluntary contribution of many thousands of scientists worldwide</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">. We argue that it is vital that this commitment acts to stimulate scientific research </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">rather than placing a burden that may hinder scientific progress</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> and that the IPCC process, or a</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">ny modification to </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">it, must ensure this.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">IPCC </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">reports are neutral with respect to policy</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> being policy-relevant but never policy-prescriptive.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">By endorsing the IPCC reports, governments acknowledge the authority of their scientific content.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What relevance do the IPCC’s conclusions have in respect of the review of the fourth Carbon Budget? </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">The report concluded that “Continued emissions of greenhouse gases will cause further warming and changes in all components of the climate system. Limiting climate change will require substantial and sustained reductions of greenhouse gas emissions.” It also concluded “</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Cumulative emissions of CO2 largely determine global mean surface warming by the late 21st century and beyond. Most aspects of climate change will persist for many centuries even if emissions of CO2 are stopped. This represents a substantial multi-century climate change commitment created by past, present and future emissions of CO2.” We suggest that both these conclusions may be of relevance to the review of the fourth Carbon Budget.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Note 1</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">A list of members of the CSCG and Council</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">CSCG members:</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Dr </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Emily Shuckburgh (Chair)</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Dr </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Ed Hawkins</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Ian </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Strangeways</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Prof </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">John Mitchell</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Prof </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Tim Palmer</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Prof </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Rowan Sutton</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Council members:</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Prof </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Joanna Haigh (President)</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Jennie Campbell</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Prof </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Ellie Highwood</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Dr </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">David Stevenson</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Rob Varley</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Dr </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Bob Riddaway</span><br /><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:12pt">Alan Radford</span><br /